## What Is the Cushion vs Round Diamond Difference?

The cushion cut vs round diamond comparison is not a quality comparison — it is a shape comparison between two different optical personalities. The round brilliant is a circular diamond with 57 or 58 precisely angled facets optimised over more than a century of gemological science for maximum white light return. The cushion cut is a square-to-rectangular diamond with softened corners and a brilliant-type facet arrangement descended from the Old Mine Cut of the 18th and 19th centuries.

I'm **Farzana Hasan**, a GIA Expert. The [cushion cut vs round diamond](/cushion-cut-diamond) decision is one I discuss with buyers every week. The buyers who choose round almost always cite it as the "safe choice" — the most popular, the most recognised, the one that maximises resale value.

The buyers who choose cushion almost always cite fire, vintage character, and the ability to buy a better quality stone for the same budget. Both priorities are valid. Neither cut is objectively better — and the 69% price premium at 1ct for round means the "safe choice" carries a significant financial cost.

This guide covers every dimension: sparkle differences, price at 1ct and 2ct, face-up size, clarity requirements, vintage appeal, lab grown options, and the final verdict by buyer type. For the full cushion shape overview, see the [cushion cut diamond guide](/cushion-cut-diamond). For round diamond pricing at every carat weight, see the [1 carat round diamond price guide](/1-carat-round-diamond-price).

---

## The Brilliance Gap

The Brilliance Gap is the optical difference between round and cushion cuts that drives the round's price premium — and that most buyers overestimate when they haven't seen both cuts side-by-side in person.

**What the round does better.** The round brilliant's 57-facet arrangement is the result of more than a century of mathematical optimisation, beginning with Marcel Tolkowsky's 1919 ideal proportions paper and refined continuously since. At optimal crown and pavilion angles (approximately 34.5° crown / 40.8° pavilion), a round brilliant achieves a theoretical light return of approximately 95–98% — the highest of any diamond cut. This produces the round's distinctive optical signature: intense, even white light return across the entire face-up, with balanced scintillation (rapid on/off sparkle as the stone and viewer move).

**What the cushion does differently.** The cushion modified brilliant's varied facet angles and additional pavilion facets produce a different optical output. The crushed ice pattern distributes light return across many small, uniform reflections — high-density sparkle with less directional intensity than a round. More importantly, the cushion's facet geometry produces more fire (spectral colour dispersion — the rainbow flashes at facet boundaries) relative to a round of equivalent colour grade.

Buyers who love fire — the coloured flash component of diamond sparkle — consistently prefer cushion to round in side-by-side comparisons, even when they enter the comparison expecting to prefer round.

**The honest reality of The Brilliance Gap.** Round has superior white light return on paper. In a finished ring, on a hand, under the mixed lighting of everyday life — indoor artificial light, natural daylight, evening restaurant lighting — most observers cannot identify which is "more brilliant" without a simultaneous side-by-side comparison. The Gap is real at a technical measurement level.

It is much smaller than the 69% price premium suggests at a perceptual level. The correct framing: round is the optimised choice for maximum white sparkle; cushion is the choice for more fire and a softer, vintage-derived silhouette at a substantially lower price.

![Cushion vs Round Diamond: The Brilliance Gap — optical difference and price comparison infographic](/images/cushion-vs-round-brilliance-gap.avif)

