## Face-Up Size: Cushion vs Round

At the same carat weight, round brilliants face up marginally larger than cushion modified brilliants. A 1ct round measures approximately 6.4–6.5mm in diameter; a 1ct cushion modified brilliant measures approximately 6.5mm × 6.5mm in maximum dimension. The round's circular outline covers more uniform area than the cushion's square outline with rounded corners — the circle captures more consistent face-up geometry.

**The practical size difference.** The face-up area difference between a 1ct round (approximately 33mm²) and a 1ct cushion (approximately 32mm² for a typical modified brilliant) is less than 3%. Under normal conditions — a ring worn on a hand, viewed in conversation — this difference is not perceptible without a reference point. The "which is bigger" question is functionally a draw at 1ct and 2ct, resolved only under direct side-by-side millimetre measurement.

**Where the cushion gains back face-up.** The cushion's elongated variants (LW ratio 1.10–1.25) can face up larger per carat than the round at equivalent weight, because the elongated shape distributes more weight across finger length. An elongated cushion at 1.15 LW at 2ct measures approximately 9.1mm × 7.9mm — more finger coverage than a 2ct round at 8.1mm diameter, even though the round has more circular face-up area. For buyers who want maximum finger coverage rather than maximum circular face-up, the elongated cushion is the superior size play.

