## Sparkle: Cushion Modified Brilliant vs Round Brilliant

Both cuts are brilliant-type — they use brilliant-style facet arrangements to maximise light return. The sparkle comparison resolves not to "which sparkles more" but to "which sparkle character do you prefer."

**Round sparkle character.** A GIA Excellent round brilliant at ideal proportions (34.5° crown, 40.8° pavilion, 55–58% table) produces maximum white light return — the intense, even, full-face sparkle that makes rounds unmistakeable under bright lighting. The round's scintillation pattern is rapid and even: as the stone moves, bright and dark facets alternate in a balanced, symmetric pattern across the circular face. This is the sparkle that most people visualise when they think "diamond."

**Cushion modified brilliant sparkle character.** The cushion modified brilliant's crushed ice pattern distributes light across many small, uniform micro-reflections. The overall brightness is lower than a round at identical quality grades — but the fire (colour at facet boundaries) is noticeably higher. Under warm incandescent light, a cushion modified brilliant shows more visible rainbow colour at its facet edges than a round of the same colour grade.

Under direct sunlight, the cushion's fire is vivid and creates an entirely different visual experience from the round's predominantly white return.

**The cushion brilliant alternative.** The cushion brilliant sub-type (larger, chunkier facets — "Cushion Brilliant" on the GIA cert rather than "Cushion Modified Brilliant") produces a sparkle pattern closer to the round — larger individual flash zones, more visible contrast, less crushed ice character. Buyers who want cushion's silhouette but prefer round-adjacent sparkle should filter specifically for cushion brilliant. See the [cushion cut diamond guide](/cushion-cut-diamond) for the full sub-type comparison.

---

## Clarity: Does Round or Cushion Hide Inclusions Better?

Both round and cushion modified brilliant are among the most forgiving cuts for hiding inclusions — VS2 is the practical eye-clean minimum for both cuts in most cases.

**Round clarity performance.** The round brilliant's intense, uniform light return creates a high level of optical "noise" across the stone's face — inclusions in the mid-to-lower crystal are effectively masked by the sparkle overlay at VS2 and many SI1 clarity grades. A GIA Excellent round at VS2 is reliably eye-clean; a significant proportion of GIA Excellent rounds at SI1 are also eye-clean, requiring individual stone verification via HD video.

**Cushion modified brilliant clarity performance.** The crushed ice pattern in cushion modified brilliants is also highly forgiving of inclusions — the dense, uniform micro-reflection texture hides inclusions similarly to round at VS2. The practical minimum clarity for cushion modified brilliant is VS2 for reliable eye-cleanliness without video verification. SI1 at 1ct cushion modified brilliant can be eye-clean, but requires individual stone HD video confirmation.

**Cushion brilliant clarity difference.** The cushion brilliant sub-type (larger facets, less crushed ice) is less forgiving of inclusions than either round or cushion modified brilliant. Cushion brilliant at VS2 should be verified with HD video; VS1 is the safe floor for reliable eye-cleanliness without verification. This clarity difference is the main practical trade-off when choosing cushion brilliant over modified brilliant at the same budget.

---

## Lab Grown: Cushion vs Round

In the lab grown market, the price gap between cushion and round cuts narrows substantially but does not fully close.

**Lab round pricing at 1ct.** A GIA D-IF Ideal lab round at 1ct costs [$1,560](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28023534?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) — cheaper than a natural G-VS1 Ideal cushion at $1,891. This is the lab market's most striking arithmetic: a D-IF lab round (top grade) is less expensive than a natural G-VS1 cushion (mid-tier quality). For buyers who have been comparing natural rounds and natural cushions, the lab round at $1,560 resets the entire decision framework.

**Lab cushion pricing.** An [IGI 1.5ct E-VVS2 Excellent Cushion Modified lab at $1,422](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28961887?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) delivers 50% more face-up weight than a 1ct lab round for $138 less. In the lab market, the question is not "can I afford round?" — at $1,560 for D-IF Ideal, lab round is accessible. The question is whether you want the round's optical personality at 1ct or the cushion's fire and larger face-up at 1.5ct for slightly less money.

**Which lab cut to choose.** Lab round is the correct lab choice if you specifically want the round brilliant's optical signature and the social recognition that comes with the universally known round shape. Lab cushion is the correct lab choice if you want more fire, a vintage-derived silhouette, or more face-up size per dollar. In the lab market, the price difference between the two cuts is small enough that the decision should be made entirely on aesthetic preference.

![Cushion vs Round Diamond: The Lab Reset — natural vs lab price comparison infographic](/images/cushion-vs-round-lab-reset.avif)

> "In the lab market, I stop the price comparison conversation early because it almost resolves itself. Lab D-IF Ideal round at $1,560 and lab 1.5ct E-VVS2 Excellent cushion at $1,422 are $138 apart — less than the cost of a setting upgrade. At that price difference, the cushion vs round decision in lab is purely: which shape do you want to wear every day?
>
> For buyers entering this comparison from natural diamonds, the lab market resets everything. The round that cost $3,200 natural costs $1,560 lab. The cushion that saved $1,309 versus natural round now saves only $138. In lab, there is no meaningful financial case for cushion over round — only an aesthetic one." — Farzana Hasan, **[Diamond Critics](https://diamondcritics.com/about-farzana/)**

