## Frequently Asked Questions

### Is cushion cut cheaper than round diamond?

Yes — significantly. At 1ct G-VS1 GIA-certified quality, a cushion modified brilliant Ideal cut costs $1,891 versus a round brilliant Excellent cut at $3,200 — round is 69% more expensive. The gap persists across quality tiers: at F-VS1 1ct, cushion is $2,064 versus round at $3,830.

At 2ct, the gap narrows at the G tier but widens again at premium quality. In lab grown diamonds, the gap is much smaller — lab round D-IF Ideal starts at $1,560, very close to lab cushion equivalents.

### Which sparkles more — cushion or round?

Both produce brilliant-type sparkle, but with different optical characters. Round maximises white light return (scintillation) — the intense, even white sparkle most people associate with "diamond." Cushion modified brilliant produces more fire (rainbow colour dispersion) and a crushed ice pattern of fine, uniform sparkle. In controlled comparisons, observers cannot reliably identify which is "more sparkly" without a simultaneous side-by-side — the difference is in character, not intensity.

### Is round or cushion bigger for the same carat weight?

Round faces up marginally larger than cushion modified brilliant at the same carat weight — approximately 3% more face-up area at 1ct (33mm² round vs 32mm² cushion). In practice, this difference is imperceptible without side-by-side measurement. Elongated cushion cuts at 1.10–1.25 LW ratio face up larger per carat than round by covering more finger length.

For buyers who want maximum face-up coverage, 1.5ct elongated cushion at $1,422 lab is larger than 1ct round at $1,560 lab — 50% more carat weight for less money.

### What clarity do I need for a cushion vs round at 1ct?

Both cuts are reliably eye-clean at VS2 without individual stone verification. SI1 at 1ct is eye-clean in many round brilliants and most cushion modified brilliants, but requires HD video verification per stone. Cushion brilliant sub-type (not modified brilliant) is slightly less forgiving — VS1 is the safe floor without video verification.

Neither cut requires VS1 as a minimum at 1ct for eye-cleanliness; VS2 is sufficient for both with the note that SI1 cushion modified brilliants can be verified via Blue Nile's 360° HD video.

### Why is round more expensive than cushion?

Round's price premium reflects three compounding factors: higher rough diamond waste in cutting (round loses more of the original crystal than cushion), highest consumer demand of any cut globally (~50–60% of all diamond sales), and a decades-long premium for the cut's technical optimisation. Cushion cuts have lower rough waste and lower relative demand, making them significantly cheaper per carat at equivalent quality grades.

### Which is better for an engagement ring — cushion or round?

Neither is objectively better. Round is the conventional choice offering maximum light return and strongest resale value. Cushion offers more fire, vintage character, and a 30–69% saving at equivalent quality.

The better choice is whichever shape the wearer prefers after seeing both in a ring, on a hand — not the one that scores higher on paper metrics neither buyer will measure in daily wear.

### Does cushion cut look as good as round?

Yes — and in certain aesthetic contexts, cushion reads as more distinctive and elegant than round. Under warm incandescent lighting, cushion's fire is more visible than round's; in restaurant and candle lighting, cushion modified brilliants show vivid colour dispersion that rounds do not match. Round looks better under harsh overhead lighting where its maximised white return is most visible.

The better-looking cut depends entirely on the lighting environment and the observer's optical preference.

### Is cushion cut vintage?

Yes — the cushion cut is historically descended from the Old Mine Cut, the dominant diamond cut from the mid-18th to the early 20th century. All genuine antique engagement diamonds from the Victorian, Edwardian, and Art Deco periods are cushion-adjacent cuts. A modern cushion cut in a milgrain or halo setting is the most historically authentic interpretation of a vintage engagement ring.

Round brilliants in vintage settings look vintage-inspired but are not period-authentic as a cut.

### Which has better resale value — cushion or round?

Round has significantly better resale value. The round's universal demand — accounting for 50-60% of all diamond sales — makes it the most liquid diamond on the secondhand market. Round diamonds typically retain 40-50% of retail value on resale.

Cushion diamonds retain less due to lower universal demand and the cut's relatively recent popularity growth. If resale value is a priority in the buying decision, round is the practical choice — the premium over cushion is partly buying future liquidity.

### Can I get a lab round for less than a natural cushion?

Yes. A GIA D-IF Ideal lab round at 1ct is [$1,560](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28023534?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) — less than a natural G-VS1 Ideal cushion at $1,891. In lab, a D-IF round (top grade in both colour and clarity) is accessible at a lower price than the natural cushion entry.

This is the most striking price comparison in the cushion vs round analysis: if origin does not matter, the lab round eliminates the price argument for natural cushion entirely.

### Which cut is better in yellow gold — cushion or round?

Both cuts look excellent in yellow gold. Cushion's warm fire is enhanced by yellow gold's warm tonal reflection — the metal amplifies the colour dispersion that cushion produces. Round in yellow gold is also excellent, but the round's optimised white return creates a contrast with the warm metal that some buyers find less harmonious at G-H colour grades.

Cushion modified brilliant at G-H colour in yellow gold reads as visually warm and rich; round at G-H in yellow gold can show the stone's body warmth more visibly against the white light return.

### What is The Brilliance Gap?

The Brilliance Gap is the optical difference between round and cushion cuts: round achieves the highest mathematical white light return of any cut (approximately 95-98% light return at ideal proportions); cushion modified brilliant achieves lower white light return but more fire (rainbow colour dispersion). The gap is real at a technical measurement level. In everyday wearing conditions — mixed indoor/outdoor light, hand movement, social distances — it is perceived as a difference in optical personality rather than a quality gap.

Round: more white sparkle. Cushion: more coloured fire.

### Is cushion or round better for a halo ring?

Both are excellent halo candidates. Cushion in a cushion-shaped halo creates the most visually coherent result — the halo follows the cushion's pillow outline precisely and the stone fills the setting naturally. Round in a round halo is the classic engagement ring configuration and looks excellent.

The halo at 1ct adds approximately 0.5ct of visual face-up area to either cut, making the combined visual equivalent of a 1.5ct+ stone. Neither cut has a clear advantage in halo settings — the choice remains a silhouette preference.

